<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Peck; PHOTO: Staller  </CAPTION>
<LEADPARA>  (check) The Honorable Ilona Staller, giggling and squirming, introduced
legislation in Rome Tuesday. Her law would reopen brothels, closed since 1958,
on the argument that those working girls should be taken off the street and
removed from the danger of pimp exploitation. All of which shows us that,
whatever you might say about the porn star lawmaker, she does know her
constituency.;    (check) Our spies in Washington say Ken Burns (PBS's "Civil
War") is encamped at the Embassy Row Hotel filming interviews for a five-hour
series on baseball. He'll talk to such local fanatics as George Will,
Richmond-Times Dispatch writer Charlie McDowell and Washington Post sports
scribbler Tom Boswell.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ALSO NOTED . . .  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  People
Information in this column is from Mercury New wire services  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     (check) Alexandra Ripley's 700-page sequel to "Gone With the Wind" is set
for a Sept. 25 publication. Its unwieldy title: "Scarlett: The Sequel, to
Margaret Mitchell's 'Gone With the Wind.' " Its price: $24.95.;    (check)
Gossip slingers in New York tell us that the Adrian Pasdar-Cecilia Peck
wedding is a dead issue. Pasdar has been replaced in the heart of Gregory
Peck's daughter by Richard Baskin, son of Baskin-Robbins . . . which makes
this story a scoop.;    (check) The queen of the Maori people of New Zealand,
Te Arikinui Dame Te Atairangikaahu, has accepted an invitation to come to
Memphis, Tenn., for the city's May International Festival. Festival
spokeswoman Lucy Shaw explains: "To tell you the truth, I don't know why she's
coming.";    (check) Olivia Ward, wife of New York police commissioner Ben
Ward, has landed a regular role on "The Cosby Show," as a buddy of Dr.
Huxtable's mother.  </TEXT>
